# Next.js Production Rules

You are building production Next.js apps with TypeScript. Prefer modern App Router patterns and server-first architecture.

## Architecture and Routing
- Use App Router (`app/`) for all new routes; do not introduce Pages Router (`pages/`) unless required by legacy constraints.
- Organize routes by domain and keep route segments focused and shallow where possible.
- Use route groups and parallel routes intentionally, only when they simplify UX or layout boundaries.

## Server vs Client Components
- Default to Server Components for pages, layouts, and data-heavy UI.
- Add `'use client'` only when client-side interactivity, browser APIs, or client hooks are required.
- Keep client component boundaries small to minimize bundle size.
- Do not pass non-serializable values from server to client components.

## Data Fetching and Mutations
- Fetch data on the server by default using `async` Server Components.
- Use Server Actions for mutations and form submissions when appropriate.
- Validate all mutation inputs on the server boundary.
- Revalidate cache intentionally (`revalidatePath`, `revalidateTag`) after successful mutations.
- Avoid client-side fetching for data that can be rendered server-side.

## API Endpoints
- Prefer Route Handlers in `app/**/route.ts` for API endpoints.
- Return typed, structured JSON responses and consistent error shapes.
- Keep route handlers thin; move business logic to domain/service modules.

## Performance and Assets
- Use `next/image` for non-trivial images and remote/local optimization.
- Define width/height or `fill` with constrained containers to avoid layout shift.
- Use dynamic imports for heavy client-only modules when it reduces initial bundle.
- Avoid unnecessary client state that duplicates server-rendered data.

## SEO and Metadata
- Use the Metadata API (`export const metadata` or `generateMetadata`) for SEO.
- Provide meaningful `title`, `description`, and canonical metadata per route.
- Ensure Open Graph/Twitter metadata for shareable pages.

## Edge Runtime Awareness
- Choose runtime deliberately (`edge` vs `nodejs`) based on dependencies and latency needs.
- Avoid Node-only APIs when targeting Edge runtime.
- Keep edge handlers lightweight and low-latency.

## TypeScript and Quality
- Assume `strict: true`; do not use `any` in route params, loaders, or components.
- Type `params`, `searchParams`, and API payloads explicitly.
- Prefer shared schema validation (e.g., Zod) for request/response contracts.
- Keep page/layout files lean; move reusable logic into `lib/` or feature modules.

## Testing Expectations
- Unit test server utilities and domain logic with Vitest/Jest.
- Integration test route handlers and critical Server Actions.
- Add E2E coverage (Playwright/Cypress) for core user journeys.

## Delivery Expectations
- Output should pass build, type-check, lint, and tests.
- Favor server-first, cache-aware, and SEO-complete implementations.
